    "body": "# Background\r\nWhen using FP4 quantization with the glm4.5-air model, the inference outputs may contain corrupted/garbled text. #8814 \r\n# Root Cause\r\nThe quantization operator in sglang used `torch.empty` to create tensors;\r\n* During padding, `empty` could introduce random values;\r\n* These random values were later converted into NaN when mapped to nvfp4 format;\r\n* In glm4.5’s first MLP layer, the intermediate size is 10944, which under tp=2 triggers padding. This may caused NaN values to be introduced into the matrix and propagated into subsequent GEMM computations;\r\n* Therefore, the issue is always triggered in glm4.5’s first layer. In other layers or other models, the same issue may also occur whenever irregular shapes cause padding during quantization.\r\n# Fix\r\n* Replace torch.empty with explicitly initialized tensors (e.g., torch.zeros);\r\n* Ensure padding regions are zeroed out, preventing random values from being converted to NaN in nvfp4 format and propagated downstream.\r\n# Validation\r\n* After the fix, glm4.5-air FP4 inference no longer produces corrupted output;\r\n* Multiple benchmarks ran successfully with correct results.\r\n\r\n<img width=\"5114\" height=\"298\" alt=\"image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/8d47768d-98e1-4e4c-a859-6f30ddc19012\" />\r\n\r\nBy @Azure-Tang and @qiuqiu10",
